track_notes: Park at the entrance to an abandoned road (N36.32453 W113.19193). The road is marked with a sign the prohits vehicles and hang gliders. Hike about 3 miles down the rowd. Stay east at a junction (N36.30740 W113.18720Â°) to avoid a large elevation change. Leave the road at N36.29826 W113.16974 and head up the hill. The biggest challenge on this hike were: (1) avoiding prickly brush; (2) a bit of cinder on Mt Emma and slightly loose footing. Walk along a fence at N36.28903 W113.17108. The upper area is an open forest of pine. Lood for redtailed hawks.  I saw a nesting pair on the south edge of the pine trees. I had fun climbing over a lava pile, the entrance to which I cut at N36.27011 W113.17021.  Along the road you might consider keeping an eye out for and pulling out some old irrigation tubing.  I pulled out a couple hundred feet of this, old beer bottles (from the 1970s) and a empty vodka jug.  I took a feew scenic detours and logged 13 miles with 9 liters water. Have fun.
